===Chapel Architecture=== [[File:Baptist Church, Lincoln.jpg|thumb|Baptist Church, Mint Street, Lincoln]] [[File:Potters Bar Old Baptist Church.jpg|thumb|left|Potters Bar Old Baptist Church]] [[File:Baptist Church, Brown Street, Salisbury - geograph.org.uk - 195730.jpg|thumb|left|Baptist Church, Brown Street, Salisbury]]
In the 1860s Romanesque architecture became a popular style of architecture for [[Dissenting]] chapels. Possibly this was intended to give the impression that they were churches similar to [[Anglican]] churches and they are often referred to as churches rather than chapels. This form of architecture was often chosen by the [[Baptists]]. This architecture is an adapted and debased form of [[Italianate]] Romanesque as seen at the [[Potters Bar|Potter's Bar]] Old Baptist Church in Hertfordshire in 1859.<ref>[http://www.pbbc.org.uk/home Potters Bar Baptist Church]</ref> The Baptist Church in Brown Street [[Salisbury]] of the 1880s is similar in bright red brick and was built in the 1880s. It is noticeably more ''archaeologically correct'' in its use of arched windows and the entrance door. A Baptist Chapel of 1870 by the Lincoln architects [[Michael Drury|Drury and Mortimer]], the Mint Lane Baptist Chapel in Lincoln is in a debased Italianate Romanesque revival style but has a surprising tower in the [[castellated]] Gothic style.{{sfn|Antram|Pevsner|Harris|1989|p=521–2}}
[[File:Grimsby Synagogue - geograph.org.uk - 141647.jpg|thumb|Grimsby Synagogue]]
===Synagogues=== The Romanesque revival was also a style of architecture that appealed to Jewish communities and there are examples of Synagogues in this style. One of these is the synagogue built adjacent to the docks at [[Grimsby]] in Lincolnshire.
{{clear}}
===Later Romanesque Revival Churches in Scotland=== [[File:Kirk Doors - geograph.org.uk - 684906.jpg|thumb|left|Cranshaws Kirk Doors]] [[File:West Kirk (geograph 1866764).jpg|thumb|West Kirk, Sandgate, Ayr, by William Gale 1844–45]] The earliest example of Romanesque revival architecture in Scotland is the West Kirk, Sandgate, Ayr. By the architect William Gale for the Presbyterian [[Free Church of Scotland (1843–1900)|Free Church]] and built in 1844–45. The columns used for the windows are very similar to those used by Edmund Sharpe at Scotford church. In Scotland the [[Church of Scotland|Presbyterian]]s occasionally built in the Romanesque revival style, but only later in the 19th century. [[St Conan’s Kirk]] Lochawe, Agyll and Bute is an extraordinary early 20th century church on the shore of Loch Awe, built by Walter Douglas Campbell, brother of the 1st Lord Blythswood, was started in 1881, but not completed until 1930. The kirk is largely Romanesque in style, but is also mixed with other completely unrelated styles.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.britainexpress.com/attractions.htm?attraction=1082 |title=St Conan's Kirk |publisher=Britain Express |accessdate=}}</ref> Another church is Cranshaws in [[Berwickshire]]. Here the 1739 church was rebuilt in 1899 by architect George Fortune in Romanesque Revival style. {{clear}} {| align="center" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="4" style="border: 2px solid #9d9d9d;background-color:#eeeeee" valign="midlle" |- | <div align="centre"><gallery perrow="4"> File:Cranshaws Parish Church - geograph.org.uk - 1588604.jpg|Cranshaws Parish Church File:St Conan's Kirk Lochawe - geograph.org.uk - 747939.jpg|St Conan's Kirk Lochawe File:St Conan's Church, Lochawe - geograph.org.uk - 1254754.jpg|St Conan's Church, Lochawe </gallery> |}
==Sir Alfred Waterhouse and developed Romanesque Architecture== [[File:Natural History Museum 001.jpg|thumb|left|Natural History Museum 001]] [[File:Ukrainian Catholic Cathedral of the Holy Family in Exile, London, UK - Diliff.jpg|thumb|Ukrainian Catholic Cathedral of the Holy Family in Exile, London]] Interest in Romanesque Revival Architecture was renewed by Sir [[Alfred Waterhouse]]'s [[Natural History Museum]] in Kensington, which was built between 1873 and 1881.{{sfn|Stratton|1993|pp=70–77}} It was built in shades of buff coloured [[Architectural terracotta|terracotta]] and opened the way for the Romanesque style to be used for other buildings, apart from churches. Waterhouse tended to mix the architectural styles, often using decorative Romanesque arches to provide impressive entrances for his buildings, and popularised the deep red terracotta produced by manufacturer's in the [[Wrexham]] and [[Ruabon]] area of North-East Wales. This included parts of the Prudential Insurance building in London and the entrance to Strangeways Prison.
{{clear}}
===Buildings by Sir Alfred Waterhouse=== {| align="center" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="4" style="border: 2px solid #9d9d9d;background-color:#eeeeee" valign="midlle" |- | <div align="centre"><gallery perrow="4"> File:Natural History Museum 010.jpg|Natural History Museum File:Natural History Museum 004.jpg|Natural History Museum File:Natural History Museum 005.jpg|Natural History Museum File:Manchester town hall.jpg|Manchester town hall File:Holborn, Prudential Assurance building, 142 Holborn Bars, EC1 - geograph.org.uk - 667958.jpg|Holborn, Prudential Assurance building, 142 Holborn Bars, EC1 File:Royal Liverpool Infirmary 1.jpg|Royal Liverpool Infirmary File:St Elisabeths.JPG|St Elisabeths, Reddish, Stockport File:Strangeways Prison.jpg|Romanesque portal to Strangeways Prison, Manchester </gallery> |}
==Later 19th and 20th Century Romanesque Revival== [[File:Christ's Hospital Girl's School - geograph.org.uk - 653888.jpg|thumb|left|Christ's Hospital Girls School, Lincoln]] [[File:Silver Street, Lincoln.jpg|160px|thumb|42 Silver Street, Lincoln]] Waterhouse inspired other architects to build using terracotta and this material was used by [[William Watkins (architect)|William Watkins]], a Lincoln architect who very successfully used a deep red [[Ruabon]] terracotta for the Lincoln Christ's Hospital Girls School of 1893.{{sfn|Antram|Pevsner|Harris|1989|p=509}} An earlier building by Watkins of 1873, was originally built as a warehouse at 42 Silver Street, Lincoln. This uses artificial stone for Romanesque columns and arches to embellish the frontage. <ref>Survey of Lincoln, City Building Applications no. 413- 04/03/1873</ref>
===St Aidan's Church, Leeds=== [[File:StAidansChurchLS8 5QD.jpg|thumb|left|St Aidan's Church, Leeds]] [[File:St Aidans Font Leeds.jpg|thumb|Font at St Aidan's Church, Leeds]] [[File:St Aidans 2754.jpg|thumb|left|St Aidan's Church, Leeds]] [[St Aidan's Church, Leeds]] is a massive [[basilica]] church built in the tradition of Waterhouse, using red terracotta brickwork. The design was won by competition in 1889 and the church was built between 1891 and 1894 by the Newcastle architects RJ Johnson and A Crawford Hick. The style is a hybrid of Italian, French and German Romaneque and the [[Corbel table]] or moulded [[stringcourse]] below the eaves was based on that of [[Lund Cathedral]] in Sweden. The inside is sumptuously decorated with mosaic decoration by Sir [[Frank Brangwyn]] in the apse and a multi-coloured marble font with Romanesque arcading. The interior columns of the basilica have ornamental [[capital (architecture)|capital]]s in the Byzantine style.{{sfn|Leach|Pevsner|2009|pp=525–7}}
===20th Century=== [[File:Former church of All Saints, Petersham - geograph.org.uk - 794800.jpg|thumb|left|Former church of All Saints, Petersham]] [[File:St Francis' Church, Linden Road, Bournville - geograph.org.uk - 315175.jpg|thumb|St Francis' Church, Linden Road, Bournville]] In the 20th.century the use of the Romanesque revival style in church architecture appears to be restricted to brick built churches and often these churches have similarities with churches built in the [[Byzantine Revival architecture|Byzantine revival style]], which became more popular in the early years of the 20th century. Churches in the Romanesque revival style include All Saints, Bute Avenue, [[Petersham, London|Petersham]], Richmond-upon-Thames. This Romanesque revival church was designed by J Kelly and completed in 1908.
An even later example of the style is St Francis, Linden Road, Bournville, consecrated in 1925. This church was designed by Harvey and Wicks, the architects of the Bournville Estate {{clear}}
